                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-269-off1478 t18290910-269-victim2531"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-269-person2532">
                  SARAH 
                  GRIFFIN
               <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2532" type="surname" value="GRIFFIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2532" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2532" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of 
               <persName id="t18290910-269-person2533">
                  Charles 
                  Griffin
               <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2533" type="surname" value="Griffin"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2533" type="given" value="Charles"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2533" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , a <rs id="t18290910-269-viclabel1480" type="occupation">perfumer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-269-victim2531 t18290910-269-viclabel1480"></join>, of <placeName id="t18290910-269-crimeloc1481">Skinner-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-269-crimeloc1481" type="placeName" value="Skinner-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-269-crimeloc1481" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-269-off1478 t18290910-269-crimeloc1481"></join>. On the 8th of September, at half-past seven o'clock in the evening, the prisoner came and asked for some pen-knives - I showed him several; he said they were not good enough; he wished to have some with two blades, and said he wanted two of them to make a present of; I showed him some, and he chose two at 2s. 6d. a piece, but he said I ought to let him have them for 4s., which I agreed to do - he took the money out of his pocket; I was going to wrap them up, but he took them up, said he wished I might get the money, and ran out- I cried Stop thief! my brother pursued, and brought him back with them in ten minutes; I am certain of him.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. She said when I was examined that the young man who came in cut a bit out of his thumb; when she saw me at the watch-house I had my coat off, and she said I was not the man. Witness. He cut a small piece out of his thumb in opening one of the knives, and it bled at the watch-house; he was rather intoxicated, but perfectly conscious of what he was doing.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-269-person2534">
                  HENRY 
                  ANDERSON
               <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2534" type="surname" value="ANDERSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2534" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2534" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the prosecutrix's brother. I was in the next shop, which is only separated by a thin partition; I heard her cry Stop thief! and ran out; she was at her door, and pointed to a man running across the road - I pursued him across Fleet-market, and when he got to Holborn I took him; I did lose sight of him, as he got between the stalls.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-269-person2535">
                  THOMAS 
                  WILDER
               <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2535" type="surname" value="WILDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2535" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-269-person2535" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner was brought to the watch-house; there was 6s. 6d. and a farthing found on him, but no knives; there was a cut on the joint of his thumb, which the prosecutrix described; he was not very<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182909100139"></xptr>drunk - he said, what a pity it was, and that he was a hard - working man.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I came down the hill - I do not know the name of it; there was a mob of people shouting Stop thief! I ran - a man came and took hold of me, and said I had stolen two knives, which I had not.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 23.</p>

               <p>
